<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>part from someone • part with someone</xh5><p> <i>part from someone—</i>separate from a person; leave smb.’s company: Jagiello must have had great feelings for Elzbieta, for he never <u>parted from</u> her. They always journeyed together. </p><p><i>part with someone—</i>1. lose the services of a person; dismiss smb. from employment: Mr. Jackson has rendered very valuable service to the firm, and we are very sorry to <u>part with</u> him. 2. <i>= part from someone: </i>Sian was still married, though separated, having <u>parted with</u> her husband to fulfil her vocation on the stage.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression is not equivalent in meaning to the phrase <b>part company with someone</b>—1. <i>(of travel companions, etc.)</i> separate: We did a small European tour and after this tour we <u>parted company with</u> our singer Jonathan. 2. <i>disagree with a person: </i>Even those who generally agree with the headmaster would <u>part company with</u> him there.</p> </entry>
